        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-02-11 10:40:04.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1\n\nAlex, it would be great if you could rebase your ZFS iterator patch on top of this one to see if it passes the tests.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "0352171b3a3139682a6d5223a7af3e2a85fd7150",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-02-11 10:41:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nAndreas, it does pass except test 10 due to LinkEA osd-zfs uses to lookup(\"..\"). I'll rebase and disable that test with ZFS backend for a while.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "e9a09cae7920c9f11b16b09618302e0344c36022",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-02-11 10:52:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nDiable related test may make the Maloo test happy. But my real concern is that how we can improve the LFSCK to make the system available against ZFS backend when its linkEA broken. Generally, lfsck_namespace depends on the directory structure to rebuild linkEA. For ldiskfs backend, the directory structure does not depends on linkEA; but for ZFS, the \"..\" in the directory structure depends on linkEA. Such dead-dependency for ZFS backend should be resolved properly.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "2a67b0a244ed72be473ce6adbb99f70e443f2bfc",
      "author": {
